wwCon Algorithms Analysis

Eric Bridgeford

January 22, 2017

wwCon framework

This is not a machine learning algorithm, but rather, a weighted version of traditional measures of timeseries data.

Weighted Mean

\begin{equation} \mu_c = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N \pi_{i,c} x_i}{\sum_{i=1}^N \pi_{i,c}} \end{equation}

or our overall mean for a particular condition is just a weighted combination of the means at each timepoint, where our weight vector \(w\) just indicates the weight a particular condition is thought to be present at a given time point.

Weighted Covariance

For the covariance, we use the unbiased sample covariance:

\begin{equation} \Sigma_c = \frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^N \pi_{i,c} - 1}{\sum_{i=1}^N \pi_{i,c}(x_i - \mu)^T(x_i - \mu)} \end{equation}

Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test

Here, the data is clearly paired, as we would expect a relationship between correlation values taken at the within-subject level, and the within-scan level. We do not want to impose parametricity for the covariance values being analyzed, so we proceed with the non-parametric wilcoxon signed-rank test.

Pseudo Code

Nullmod

Inputs:

  1. \(ts \in \mathcal{R}^{nt, nroi}\): the timeseries data. 2.\(\pi \in \mathcal{R}^{nt, nc}\): the weight vector for each condition.

Outputs:

  1. \(\Sigma \in \mathcal{R}^{nroi, nroi, nc}\): the covariances for each condition.
  2. \(\mu \in \mathcal{R}^{nroi, nc}\): the means for each condition.

Algorithm:

  1. \(\textbf{for}\) \(c\) in \(1:nc\)
  • \(\Sigma [,,c]\) = \(cov(ts, wt=\pi[,c])\) # calculate covariance wrt any nonzero weights
  • \(\mu [,c]\) = \(mean(ts, wt=\pi[,c])\) # calculate mean wrt any nonzero weights
  1. \(\textbf{endfor}\) # Simulations
  require('MASS')
  source('./wwCon.R')
  source('../drivers/plot_one_mtx.R')

  nt <- 100
  ncond <- 2
  nroi <- 2
  mu <- array(0, dim=c(nroi, ncond))
  mu[,1] <- 3
  mu[,2] <- -3
  sigma <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, nroi, ncond))
  sigma[,,1] <- diag(nroi)
  sigma[,,2] <- diag(nroi)
  pi_v <- array(0, dim=c(nt, ncond))
  pi_v[1:50, 1] <- 1
  pi_v[51:100,2] <- 1
  
  observed_signal <- array(0, dim=c(nt, nroi))
  for (i in 1:ncond) {
    library(randomts)
    observed_signal <- pi_v[,i]*mvrnorm(n = nt, mu = mu[,i], Sigma <- sigma[,,i]) + observed_signal
  }
   
  test <- wwCon(observed_signal, pi_v)
  trusig <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, nroi, ncond))
  trusig[,,1] <- cov(observed_signal[1:50,])
  trusig[,,2] <- cov(observed_signal[51:100,])
  trumean <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, ncond))
  trumean[,1] <- mean(observed_signal[1:50,])
  trumean[,2] <- mean(observed_signal[51:100,])

Synthetic Data

Here, we will simulate what we expect to observe with the real data. We expect that if we feed in 3 conditions with unique, but consistent, covariance matrices for each simulated “subject”, we will obtain a significant difference in the covariances and means using a wilcoxon test, after aggregating the edges (in the covariance case) or the mean values (in the mean case) for each condition, and then performing a wilcoxon test between pairs of conditions.

We consider there to be 3 conditions in this case, and 3 ROIs for each over 3 subjects.

The covariance matrices for each trial type for each subject will be perfectly random, except for 1 edge (a different one for each condition) will have a covariance that is equal in all of the trials, to the maximum covariance of that edge after sampling randomly. We will, for simplicity, replace for condition \(c\) the \(i,j^{th}\) edge where \(i,j = c\) to be the edge that is maximally covariant as this will not disrupt our eigenvalues (and, hence, preserve positive-semi-definiteness). Given a covariance matrix \(\Sigma \in \mathcal{R}^{nr, nr, nc, ns}\), where \(nr\) is the number of rois, \(nc\) is the number of conditions, and \(ns\) is the number of subjects, our procedure will be:

  1. \(\textbf{for}\) \(c\) in \(1:nc\)
  • \(\Sigma_{c,c,c,:} = \max(\Sigma)\)
  1. \(\textbf{endfor}\)

This should give us an appreciable difference in performing our wilcoxon tests.

Likewise, for the means, we will sample the mean matrices for each subject randomly, except for a single ROI. Given means \(\mu \in \mathcal{R}^{nr, nc, ns}\), our procedure will be:

  1. \(\textbf{for}\) \(c\) in \(1:nc\)
  • \(\mu_{c,c,:} = \max(\mu)\)
  1. \(\textbf{endfor}\)

In this context, we will define a unique, random source covariance matrix for each condition, and then see that when we use our algorithm, the unique edge/ROI values are reflected in the wilcoxon results.

# standard equation for a random positive semi-definite matrix
random_pos_semi <- function(n) {
  pos <- array(rnorm(n*n), dim=c(n,n))
  pos <- pos*t(pos) + n*diag(n)
}

# replace the covariance edges following the procedure described above
replace_cov <- function(covs) {
  c = dim(covs)[3]
  max_covs <- max(covs)
  for (x in 1:c) {
    # set as the maximum value over all subjects for this edge
    covs[x,x,x,] <- max_covs
  }
  return(covs)
}

# replace the means following the procedure described above
replace_mean <- function(mu) {
  c=dim(mu)[2]
  max_mean <- max(mu)
  for (x in 1:c) {
    mu[x,x,] <- max_mean
  }
  return(mu)
}
nt <- 300
nroi <- 3
nsub <- 3
nscan <- 3
ncond <- 3
covs <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, nroi, ncond, nsub*nscan))
means <- array(NaN, dim=c(nroi, ncond, nsub*nscan))

subs <- c("s1", "s1", "s1", "s2", "s2", "s2", "s3", "s3", "s3")
runs <- c("r1", "r2", "r3", "s1", "r2", "r3", "r1", "r2", "r3")
# generate sources for the random normal distributions
for (x in 1:ncond) {
  for (s in 1:nsub) {
    sid <- paste("s", s, sep="")
    cov_sub <- random_pos_semi(nroi)
    mean_sub <- rnorm(nroi)
    for (n in which(subs == sid)) {
      covs[,,x,n] <- cov_sub
      means[,x,n] <- mean_sub
    }
  }
}

covs <- replace_cov(covs)
means <- replace_mean(means)

Next, we need to generate a structured pi-vector for each subject to somewhat model a hemodynamic response for an individual ROI in response to a stimulus. To do so, we generate a spike train spaced by 5 timesteps, and use a somewhat trapezoidal response window. This window will allow us to effectively compare how our wwcon model compares with null and tGMM.

get_pi_vector <- function(nt, nc, window, offset=4, overlap=4) {
  conditions <- array(0, dim=c(nt, nc)) # initialize empty condition vector
  for (cond in 1:nc) {
    conditions[seq((cond-1)*overlap + 1, nt, (nc-1)*overlap + offset), cond] <- 1
  }
  source('C:/Users/ebrid/Documents/GitHub/memory/code/R/drivers/convolve_trial_onsets.R')
  return(convolve_conditions(conditions, window))
}

window <- array(c(0, 1, 3, 4, 3, 3, 1, 0))
pi_v <- get_pi_vector(nt, ncond, window)
pi_v[1,] <- array(c(1,0,0))

pi_v <- pi_v/apply(pi_v, MARGIN=1, FUN=sum)

observed_signal <- list()
for (s in 1:(nsub*nscan)) {
  signal <- array(0, dim=c(nt, nroi))
  for (c in 1:ncond) {
    signal <- pi_v[,c]*mvrnorm(n = nt, mu = means[,i,s], Sigma <- covs[,,c,s]) + signal
  }
  observed_signal[[s]] <- signal
}
names(observed_signal) <- 1:9

  # atlas is a oro.nifti image
  plot_brain_overlay <- function(atlas, reference, values) {
    require(RColorBrewer)
    ov <- atlas
    # sort the rois so that they go low to small, which is what pipeline outputs
    roimap <- sort(unique(array(atlas@.Data)))
    roimap <- roimap[2:length(roimap)]  # ignore 0 valued roi (no region)
    for (roi in 1:length(values)) {
      if (is.nan(values[roi])) {
        ov@.Data[round(atlas@.Data) == roi] = 0
      } else {
        ov@.Data[round(atlas@.Data) == roi] = 1 - values[roi]
      }
    }
    overlay(reference, ifelse(ov > .9, ov, NA), zlim.y=c(0, 1),
            col.y=brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Oranges"))
  }
